# Tauri + React Project — Claude Code Instructions

_Origin: https://github.com/maxart/Tauri-with-AI — check upstream for newer versions of this file._

## Identity

You are working on a production Tauri v2 desktop application with a React + TypeScript frontend and a Rust backend. Follow modern best practices (2025+). Write clean, maintainable, type-safe, secure code on both sides of the IPC boundary. Prioritize correctness, security, and accessibility. Do not over-engineer.

---

## Output and Efficiency

- Return code first. Explanation after, only if non-obvious.
- No sycophantic openers, closing fluff, or restating the question.
- No unsolicited suggestions or boilerplate beyond the requested scope.
- Read before writing. One focused pass — avoid write-delete-rewrite cycles.
- If unsure, say so. Never guess file paths, crate names, or Tauri APIs.
- Code output is ASCII only (plain hyphens, straight quotes).
- Code review: state the bug, show the fix, stop. Debugging: read first, state what/where/fix.
- User instructions always override this file.

---

## Code Quality Rules

### General

- Write the simplest code that solves the problem. No speculative abstractions.
- **Minimal runtime cost.** Prefer the lighter dependency when functionality is equivalent. Desktop bundle size matters — every extra MB slows downloads and updates. Check `bundlephobia.com` for npm, `cargo bloat` for Rust.
- One React component per file (PascalCase). One Rust module per logical concern.
- Keep files under 200 lines (TS/TSX) / 300 lines (Rust). Split by responsibility.
- Do not add comments that restate the code. Only non-obvious "why".
- Do not add JSDoc or doc comments to every function. Only public APIs and complex logic.
- Remove dead code. Do not comment it out.
- Use `const` (TS) / `let` (Rust) by default. Only mutable when required.
- Prefer early returns over nested conditionals.
- Do not use `var` in TypeScript. Do not use `unsafe` in Rust without a written justification.
- Do not use TS `enum`. Use `as const` objects or union literals.

### Naming

- React components: `PascalCase` (`UserProfile.tsx`)
- React hooks: `camelCase` with `use` prefix
- Utilities: `camelCase`; Types/Interfaces: `PascalCase`; Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`
- Boolean props/state prefix: `is`, `has`, `should`, `can`
- Event handlers: `handle*`; handler props: `on*`
- Rust modules/files: `snake_case`; types: `PascalCase`; functions/vars: `snake_case`; constants: `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`
- Tauri commands: `snake_case` in Rust, auto-converted to `camelCase` in JS unless overridden.

---

## TypeScript Rules

### Strictness

- Always `strict: true`. Never disable.
- Never `any` unless interfacing with an untyped third-party library (with a one-line justification).
- Use `unknown` for genuinely unknown types.
- Enable `noImplicitAny`, `strictNullChecks`, `noUnusedParameters`, `exactOptionalPropertyTypes`.

### Types and Interfaces

- `interface` for component props; `type` for unions, intersections, computed.
- Do not use `React.FC`. Type props directly in the function signature.
- Use `React.ReactNode` for children.
- Use discriminated unions for state with distinct modes.
- Implement exhaustive switch guards (`assertNever(x: never): never`).
- Leverage inference. Do not annotate what TypeScript can infer.

### Shared Types Across the IPC Boundary

- **Single source of truth.** Generate TS types for command payloads/responses from Rust. Use `specta` + `tauri-specta`, or `ts-rs`.
- Use TS union literals, not `enum`. They map cleanly from Rust serde-tagged enums.
- If not generating, keep shared types in `src/bindings/` and audit on every command-touching PR.

---

## Rust (Backend) Rules

### Toolchain

- Stable Rust, pinned via `rust-toolchain.toml`.
- Lints: `#![warn(clippy::all, clippy::pedantic)]`, `#![deny(unsafe_code)]`.
- CI runs `cargo clippy -- -D warnings` and `cargo fmt --check`.

### Error Handling

- Use `thiserror` for typed errors in the command layer. `anyhow` only for top-level scripts, not command return types.
- **Commands that can fail MUST return `Result<T, E>` where `E: serde::Serialize`.** Tauri cannot serialize `std::io::Error`, `sqlx::Error`, etc. directly — wrap in a custom `AppError` enum with a `Serialize` impl.
- Never `.unwrap()` / `.expect()` in command handlers.
- Log internals via `tracing`/`log`. Return sanitized variants. Never leak paths, stack traces, or sensitive data.

### Async

- Use `tokio`. Mark async commands `async fn`. Use `#[tauri::command(async)]` only to bridge a sync function to async.
- **Never block the runtime.** No `std::thread::sleep` or blocking fs/HTTP inside async commands. Use `tokio::fs`, `tokio::time`, `reqwest`, or `tokio::task::spawn_blocking`.

### Ownership, Safety, Performance

- Prefer owned types (`String`, `Vec<T>`) in command signatures — borrows don't cross IPC.
- Derive `Clone`/`Debug`/`Serialize` only when needed.
- Validate all command inputs at the top of the handler (lengths, ranges, path traversal). Treat frontend input as untrusted.

---

## Tauri IPC Rules

### Commands

- Register explicitly via `tauri::generate_handler![...]`.
- Keep commands small and focused.
- Always return `Result<T, E>` when failure is possible. Never use `Option<T>` to signal errors.
- Do not pass giant payloads over IPC. For files, return a path and read via the `fs` plugin or stream via a channel.

### Channels (Rust → JS streaming)

- For progress, logs, or large/streamed data, use the Tauri v2 `Channel<T>` API — not events. Channels are typed and ordered.
- Channels outperform events for high-frequency data and avoid the global bus.

### Events (lightweight pub/sub)

- Use events for low-frequency broadcast messages (window focus, global refresh). Never for high-frequency or type-critical data.
- Always return an unlisten from `useEffect` and call it in cleanup.
- Scope to a window (`window.emit` / `window.listen`) instead of the global bus when possible.

### Frontend Invocation

- **Wrap `invoke` in typed functions in `src/ipc/`. Never call `invoke('cmd_name', ...)` directly in components.**
- Handle errors at the call site with try/catch.

---

## Tauri Security Rules (Non-Negotiable)

### Capabilities and Permissions (v2 ACL)

- Tauri v2 replaces v1's allowlist with capabilities and permissions. Files live in `src-tauri/capabilities/`.
- **Principle of least privilege.** Grant only permissions the window actually needs. Scope by window and platform.
- One capability file per logical window or feature. Reference by identifier in `tauri.conf.json`.
- Do not add permissions "just in case."
- On Linux/Android, Tauri cannot distinguish an embedded iframe from the main window — be deliberate about remote content.

### Content Security Policy

- Always configure a strict CSP in `tauri.conf.json` under `app.security.csp`. Tauri injects nonces/hashes at build time.
- **Never** `unsafe-inline` or `unsafe-eval`. If a dependency requires it, replace the dependency.
- Allow `connect-src ipc: http://ipc.localhost` and only the specific external origins you call.

### Isolation Pattern

- For apps with significant third-party frontend code, enable the isolation pattern — a sandboxed iframe that validates IPC messages before they reach Rust.

### General Hardening

- Validate every command input in Rust.
- Never pass user input directly into shell commands, SQL queries, or filesystem paths without validation and canonicalization (prevents path traversal).
- Never hardcode secrets in the frontend bundle. Store them in the OS keychain via `stronghold` or `keyring`.
- Keep `withGlobalTauri: false` (the default) unless you have a specific reason.
- Audit dependencies with `cargo audit` and `npm audit` in CI. Critical/high are blockers.

---

## Tauri State Management Rules

- Register state once with `.manage(...)` at startup.
- No `Arc` around managed state — Tauri wraps it. Use interior mutability (`Mutex`, `RwLock`) if you mutate.
- Use `tokio::sync::Mutex` for state held across `.await`; `std::sync::Mutex` for short sync critical sections only — never hold one across `.await`.
- Keep critical sections minimal. Copy/move out, drop the lock, then work.
- Inject via `tauri::State<'_, T>` in command signatures.

---

## React Component Rules

- Single responsibility per component.
- Prefer composition over configuration — pass `children` and element props, not config objects.
- Extract logic into custom hooks when a component does too much.
- Place derived values inline during render — never store them in state.

### Props

- Do not pass more than 5-7 props. Group or split.
- Destructure props in the signature; provide defaults via destructuring.
- Never spread unknown props onto DOM elements except in design-system primitives.

### Conditional Rendering

- Early returns for loading/error states. Avoid nested ternaries.
- Never `{count && <X />}` when `count` can be `0` — use `count > 0 && <X />`.

### Lists

- Stable unique `key` (`item.id`). Never array index for dynamic lists.

---

## Frontend State Management Rules

### Decision Tree

1. Server/IPC data → SWR or TanStack Query. Never copy into `useState`.
2. Local UI state → `useState`.
3. Complex local state → `useReducer`.
4. Shared (2+ components) → lift first; if 2+ levels of drilling, use React Context.
5. App-wide complex state → Zustand (preferred for Tauri apps — small, no provider).
6. Persistent state → Tauri `store` plugin or OS keychain, not `localStorage` for sensitive data.

### Principles

- Keep state as local as possible.
- Never store derived values in state.
- Functional form when updating based on previous value.
- Wrap Context consumers in a custom hook with a null-check; memoize the Context value.

---

## Data Fetching Rules (IPC + HTTP)

- Always route IPC calls through a data-fetching library (SWR or TanStack Query). Raw `invoke` in `useEffect` has no caching, dedup, or race-condition safety.
- Use conditional fetching for parameterized queries.
- Configure sensible defaults: `staleTime` ~5 min; disable retry for deterministic errors.
- Create typed wrapper hooks per command; do not call SWR/Query directly in components.
- For HTTP requests, prefer Rust `reqwest` via a command when you need CORS bypass, custom headers, or to keep tokens out of the webview.

---

## React Hooks Rules

### useEffect

- Only for synchronizing with external systems (Tauri events, DOM listeners, timers, third-party libs).
- Never for deriving state, transforming data for render, or handling user events.
- Always clean up subscriptions, listeners, and Tauri event listens.
- Handle async safely (cancelled flag) to prevent state updates after unmount.
- Include all deps. Never suppress the ESLint rule.
- Aware of StrictMode double-invocation in dev; missing cleanup is the usual bug.

### useMemo / useCallback

- Only where measurable or for memoized children.
- On React 19+ with the React Compiler, manual memoization is generally unnecessary.

### Custom Hooks

- Extract when logic repeats in 2+ components, improves readability, or needs independent testing.
- Single responsibility. Descriptive names (`useUserPermissions`, not `useData`).
- For 3+ similar IPC hooks, extract a factory.

---

## Error Handling Rules

### Frontend

- Always add Error Boundaries (app, feature, list-item levels). Use `react-error-boundary`.
- Provide recovery actions (retry, reload, home).
- Try/catch in event handlers and async functions — boundaries do not catch these.
- Wrap IPC errors in a typed `IpcError` class for consistent handling.
- Never surface raw error objects or stack traces to users.

### Backend

- Return `Result<T, AppError>` from commands (see Rust Rules).
- Log internals, return sanitized variants.
- Don't silently swallow panics in non-command code; surface visibly in debug, report via updater/Sentry in release.

---

## Performance Rules

### Frontend — Mandatory

- Route-level code splitting with `React.lazy` + `Suspense`.
- Keep the initial bundle small; lazy-load features not needed at startup.

### Frontend — Apply When Relevant

- `React.memo` on list items and components that re-render due to unused parent state.
- `useMemo` for expensive array operations on large datasets.
- Debounce rapid input (200-500 ms).
- `useTransition` for non-urgent updates.

### Frontend — Do NOT

- Memoize everything by default.
- Prematurely optimize.

### Backend / IPC

- **Minimize IPC payload size.** Every roundtrip serializes JSON. >100 KB is noticeably slow.
- Use `Channel<T>` for streaming; avoid repeated `emit` for high-frequency data.
- Do CPU-heavy work in Rust, not JS. That's why you chose Tauri.
- Move blocking I/O off the async runtime (`spawn_blocking`).
- Keep `Mutex` critical sections small.

---

## Styling Rules

### If Using Tailwind CSS

- Use `clsx` + `tailwind-merge`; create a `cn()` utility.
- Sort classes with `prettier-plugin-tailwindcss`.
- Use `@apply` sparingly.

### If Using CSS Modules

- `Component.module.css` colocated. `camelCase` class names.
- No global styles except a single `global.css`.

### General

- No runtime CSS-in-JS (styled-components, Emotion) in new projects. Use zero-runtime (Tailwind, CSS Modules, Vanilla Extract).
- Inline `style` only for truly dynamic values.
- CSS custom properties for theme values, not JS constants.

### Platform Theming

- Respect OS theme (light/dark) via `matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)')` or the `os` plugin.
- Match platform conventions: traffic-light spacing on macOS, accent color on Windows. Don't ship a website-looking app to desktop users.

---

## Accessibility Rules (Non-Negotiable)

- Semantic HTML: `<button>`, `<a>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<header>`, `<footer>`.
- Never `<div onClick>` for interactive elements.
- Every `<img>` has `alt` (empty for decorative).
- Every interactive element is keyboard accessible (Tab, Enter, Escape, Arrows).
- Every icon-only button has `aria-label`.
- Every form input has an associated `<label>` via `htmlFor`, or `aria-label`.
- Use a headless UI library (Headless UI, Radix, Ark UI, React Aria, or shadcn/ui) for complex components.
- Install and enforce `eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y` (recommended config).
- Use `useId()` for linking labels to inputs.
- Test with keyboard only, then with a screen reader (VoiceOver, NVDA).

---

## Frontend Security Rules (Non-Negotiable)

- Never `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` with user-provided content. Sanitize with DOMPurify if unavoidable.
- Enforce `react/no-danger: 'error'`.
- Use `react-markdown` for user-generated rich text.
- Validate and constrain user inputs (length, allowed chars) on both sides.
- Never store auth tokens / secrets in `localStorage`. Use the OS keychain via a Rust command.
- Never put API keys or secrets in the frontend bundle.
- Never interpolate user input into `href`.
- Keep `connect-src` origins in CSP minimal.

---

## Project Structure Rules

### Top-Level Layout

```
tauri-app/
  src/                        # React frontend
    app/                      # shell, providers, router
    pages/FeatureName/{components,hooks}
    components/               # shared reusable UI
    hooks/data/               # SWR/Query wrappers around IPC
    ipc/                      # typed invoke wrappers
    bindings/                 # generated TS types
    lib/  styles/  typings/
  src-tauri/
    src/
      main.rs                 # thin entrypoint
      lib.rs                  # builder, command registration
      commands/               # one file per domain
      error.rs                # AppError + Serialize impl
      state.rs                # AppState
    capabilities/
    icons/
    tauri.conf.json
    Cargo.toml  build.rs
  package.json  vite.config.ts  tsconfig.json
```

### Organization Principles

- Colocate feature-specific code. Promote only when shared by 2+ features.
- One component per file; one hook per file.
- Barrel files (`index.ts`) under 15 exports; prefer direct imports for large projects.
- Enforce `import/no-cycle: 'error'`. Use `simple-import-sort`.
- Use path aliases (`@/components`, `@/ipc`, `@/hooks`).
- In Rust, prefer `pub(crate)` over `pub`.

---

## Testing Rules

### Frontend Tests

- Vitest (Vite projects) or Jest. React Testing Library for components.
- Mock Tauri APIs with `@tauri-apps/api/mocks` — do not launch a webview for unit tests.
- Test behavior, not implementation.
- Query by role first, then label, then text. `getByTestId` is last resort.
- `userEvent`, not `fireEvent`.
- No snapshot tests except for very stable UI.

### Backend Tests

- Co-locate unit tests with `#[cfg(test)] mod tests`.
- For command integration tests, use Tauri's mock runtime (`tauri::test::mock_builder`, `mock_context(noop_assets())`) — no native webview required.
- Use `mockall` for trait mocks; avoid mocking concrete structs.

### End-to-End Tests

- WebDriver via `tauri-driver` (Linux + Windows; macOS unsupported as of 2025 — no WKWebView driver). Use manual smoke tests on macOS.
- Alternatives: Playwright against a dev server for frontend-only flows.
- Test the critical path and cross-page navigation.

### Coverage

- Every project must have tests. `passWithNoTests: true` is a red flag.
- CI must run: frontend tests, `cargo test`, build smoke test.

---

## Tauri Plugins Rules

- Prefer official plugins (`tauri-apps/plugins-workspace`) over hand-rolling.
- Common official plugins: `fs`, `dialog`, `shell`, `opener`, `os`, `store`, `sql`, `updater`, `notification`, `window-state`, `single-instance`, `stronghold`, `log`, `deep-link`.
- Always grant plugin permissions explicitly in capabilities; never enable blanket `allow-*` if you only need one.
- Pin plugin versions to the same Tauri major (2.x). Mismatched majors will not build.
- For custom plugins, follow the official template.

---

## Build, Bundle, and Distribution Rules

### Configuration

- Keep `tauri.conf.json` minimal and committed.
- Set a stable `identifier` (reverse-DNS) before first release — changing later breaks notifications, autolaunch, app data paths.
- Keep versions in `tauri.conf.json` and `Cargo.toml` in sync.
- `beforeDevCommand` / `beforeBuildCommand` must run the frontend build; `frontendDist` points at the build output.

### Updater

- `tauri-plugin-updater`. **Signatures are mandatory** — you cannot ship unsigned updates.
- Generate keys once (`npx @tauri-apps/cli signer generate`). Private key as CI secret. Losing it = no more updates; leaking it = attacker impersonation.
- Public key lives in `tauri.conf.json`; private key never in the repo.
- Host `latest.json` at a stable URL (GitHub Releases, S3, CrabNebula Cloud).
- Prompt users for consent before installing.

### Code Signing and Notarization

- **macOS:** Developer ID Application + notarization required. WebView entitlements `com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit` and `com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory` are mandatory — without them the app crashes on launch after notarization.
- **Windows:** Authenticode. Azure Trusted Signing or hardware/EV certs for production.
- **Linux:** AppImage / .deb / .rpm; GPG signing recommended.
- Never check certs/keys into the repo. Use CI secrets.
- Automate with GitHub Actions and Tauri's official action.

### Environment Variables

- Vite: prefix with `VITE_` to expose to the frontend bundle; unprefixed are build-time only.
- Commit `.env.example`; never `.env` with secrets.
- Never put secrets in `VITE_*` — they end up in the shipped installer.

### Bundle Size

- Track bundle and installer sizes across releases.
- `cargo bloat`, `vite-bundle-visualizer` periodically.
- Release profile: `strip = true`, `lto = true`, `codegen-units = 1`.
- Never ship source maps to production unless served behind auth.

### CI/CD Guardrails

- Do not modify CI files without explicit user approval.
- Do not add `--no-verify`, `--force`, or skip flags.
- CI must run: `tsc --noEmit`, `eslint .`, frontend tests, `cargo clippy -- -D warnings`, `cargo fmt --check`, `cargo test`, and a release `tauri build` smoke test across macOS + Windows + Linux.

---

## Tooling Rules

### Required

- TypeScript strict mode.
- ESLint with: `typescript-eslint/recommendedTypeChecked`, `eslint-plugin-react`, `eslint-plugin-react-hooks`, `eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y` (recommended), `eslint-plugin-simple-import-sort`, `eslint-plugin-import` (`no-cycle: 'error'`).
- Prettier.
- Husky + lint-staged (cover `*.{ts,tsx}` and run `cargo fmt`/`clippy` on `*.rs` changes).
- Rust: `clippy`, `rustfmt`, `cargo-deny` or `cargo-audit`.

### ESLint Rules to Enforce

- `react/no-danger: error`
- `react/jsx-no-bind: warn` (disable if using React Compiler)
- `import/no-cycle: error`
- `simple-import-sort/imports: error`
- `no-console: [warn, { allow: [warn, error] }]`

### Recommended

- `vite-plugin-checker`, `prettier-plugin-tailwindcss`.
- React DevTools + SWR/Query DevTools (dev only).
- `tracing-subscriber` for structured Rust logs.

---

## Large Project Maintenance Rules

### Dependencies

- `npm audit` and `cargo audit` monthly or in CI; critical/high are blockers.
- One major bump per PR.
- Pin majors in `package.json` and `Cargo.toml`; commit lockfiles.
- `npx depcheck` (JS), `cargo machete` (Rust) for unused deps.

### Dead Code

- Delete unused components, hooks, commands, and rolled-out feature flags.
- `noUnusedLocals` / `noUnusedParameters`. `ts-unused-exports` and `cargo +nightly udeps` periodically.

### Refactoring

- Only refactor when asked or required. Scope tightly — one thing per PR.
- Ensure tests exist before refactoring; write them first if not.
- Flag tech debt to the user; do not silently fix.

### Incremental Migration

- Never big-bang. Old and new can coexist temporarily.
- Document the canonical pattern in this file (e.g., "New commands MUST use `AppError`").

### Performance Budgets

- `size-limit` for frontend; track Rust binary size in CI.
- Monitor app startup and memory in production (telemetry).
- Check `bundlephobia.com` before adding deps. Prefer smaller: `date-fns`/`dayjs` over `moment`; native JS over `lodash`; `fetch` over `axios`; `crypto.randomUUID()` over `uuid`; `clsx` over `classnames`; SWR/TanStack Query over Apollo.

---

## When Creating a New Tauri + React Project

1. `npm create tauri-app@latest` → React + TypeScript + Vite
2. `strict: true` in `tsconfig.json`
3. Install ESLint + plugins listed above
4. Install Prettier + `prettier-plugin-tailwindcss` (if Tailwind)
5. Husky + lint-staged (TS + Rust)
6. Data-fetching library (SWR or TanStack Query)
7. `react-error-boundary` and a headless UI library
8. Directory structure (`src/ipc/`, `src-tauri/src/commands/`, etc.)
9. Add `thiserror`; create `AppError` with `Serialize` impl
10. Set up `tauri-specta` or `ts-rs` for shared types
11. Configure strict CSP + minimal capabilities
12. Install only the plugins you need
13. Generate updater keys; store private key as CI secret
14. Decide reverse-DNS `identifier` before first release
15. CI matrix: macOS + Windows + Linux, build + test
16. Integration test (mocked IPC) for critical path
17. Error Boundaries at app and feature levels
18. Commit `.env.example`

---

## When Working on an Existing Tauri + React Project

1. Read both frontend and `src-tauri/` before changing — IPC contracts are fragile.
2. Follow existing conventions even if they differ from these rules. Consistency beats theory.
3. Do not refactor unrelated code.
4. Do not add types/comments/docs to code you did not change.
5. Do not introduce new libraries, plugins, or capabilities without user approval.
6. Match existing naming, organization, style.
7. Audit capabilities before adding a command.
8. Run frontend tests + `cargo test` before claiming done.
9. `cargo clippy -- -D warnings` and `tsc --noEmit` before committing.

---

## Checklist Before Completing Any Task

- [ ] TypeScript compiles zero errors (`npx tsc --noEmit`)
- [ ] ESLint zero errors (`npx eslint .`)
- [ ] Frontend tests pass (`npm test`)
- [ ] Rust compiles with zero warnings (`cargo build`)
- [ ] `cargo clippy -- -D warnings` passes
- [ ] `cargo fmt --check` passes
- [ ] Rust tests pass (`cargo test`)
- [ ] Release build succeeds (`npm run tauri build`) since last dep change
- [ ] New commands return `Result<T, AppError>` and are registered
- [ ] New commands have explicit, scoped permissions — no blanket `allow-*`
- [ ] No `unsafe` in Rust without justification
- [ ] No `.unwrap()` / `.expect()` in command handlers
- [ ] No `any` in TS without justification
- [ ] No unsanitized `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`
- [ ] CSP unchanged or tightened
- [ ] No secrets / tokens / API keys in the frontend bundle
- [ ] New IPC calls wrapped in `src/ipc/`
- [ ] Event listeners cleaned up on unmount
- [ ] New interactive elements keyboard accessible
- [ ] Images have alt text
- [ ] List items use stable unique keys
- [ ] No commented-out code
- [ ] No `console.log` / `dbg!` in production
- [ ] No hardcoded API URLs
- [ ] No CI/CD files modified without approval
- [ ] New deps justified (size checked)

